<br>
I broke out the ole chalkboard today and generated some information of possible interest to wizards.<br>
<br>
In arcaphysics we know that Mana is channeled more easily the more that we use it and the harder that we tend to concentrate. Meaning - If we keep casting, we keep getting experienced, and in turn better find use for the mana that we channel. So, if you were to channel quick, and cast quick, your concentration would be less likely be broken. This has been the common myth throughout the arcane sciences, however I am about to dispell that myth. It is not always the Speed of the cast, nor the Damage of the cast. Both things must be held in equal calculations. +There are some spells that were crafted by men that loved to hear their own words, they saw casting as a poetic artform. Later these casters became Bards but that is a whole different story. What we have in our spellbooks today are some of these pieces of artwork, but if carefully studied we can see that their place can be in a museum rather than our spellbooks. We also know of the one to three word spells that are extremely easy to cast. A wiggle of the nose or a quick flick of our elbow and out the spell goes. Very easy and very quick. This form of casting was created by the lazier of our peers, and not for effecient, low cost, high damage casting. There are also those Braggart casters. Those full on full damage guys that blow all their mana in one wad for a specticle of oohs and ahhhhs. A true caster of Evocation does not need an Ego boost, as his relation to the elements he finds plenty of pleasure beyond superfituality of Self Esteem.<br>
<br>
So, without further ado - Here are the calculations.<br>
<br>
First off - We'll compare the Mana use per time<br>
<br>
M / DC = MPD (mana divided by damage casted = Mana per damage point)<br>
<br>
The lower the number, the less mana used for damage<br>
<br>
For example .25 means 4 mana for 16 damage / .5 means 2 mana = 4 Damage<br>
<br>
